    "body": "Modern smartphones exemplify this principle, where lithium-ion battery degradation becomes the primary limiting factor for device lifespan despite other components remaining functional for significantly longer periods.\n\n## Component Lifespan Analysis\n• Processor/Memory: Designed for 10-15 years of continuous operation\n• Display panels: Typically rated for 50,000+ hours of use (≈20 years at 8 hours daily)\n• Structural components: Aluminum/glass housing can remain intact for decades\n• Lithium-ion battery: 300-500 charge cycles before capacity drops to 80% (≈2-3 years)\n\n## Degradation Mechanism\nLithium-ion batteries experience capacity fade through lithium plating, electrolyte decomposition, and electrode structural changes. After 500 cycles, typical batteries retain only 70-80% original capacity, while other phone components maintain >95% functionality.\n\n## Quantified Impact\n• Average smartphone replacement cycle: 2.83 years globally\n• Battery degradation cited as primary replacement driver in 47% of cases\n• Functional processors and displays discarded due to battery limitations\n• Environmental cost: 6.1 billion phones discarded annually, with 80%+ of non-battery components still functional\n\n## Broader Applications\nThis principle applies across engineering systems: wind turbine gearboxes (20-year lifespan) versus 25-year tower structures, automotive timing belts (60k-100k miles) versus engine blocks (200k+ miles), and software systems where deprecated libraries force entire application rewrites.\n\nThe fundamental challenge lies in matching component lifespans or designing to replace limiting components easily."
