    "example": "Academic Publishing Industry and Knowledge Gatekeeping",
    "body": "The academic publishing system exemplifies unjust stakeholder relations, where researchers and institutions provide unpaid labor and funding while commercial publishers extract billions in profit from publicly-funded research.\n\n## Stakeholder Value Distribution Analysis\n• Publisher profit margins: 35-40% profit margins for major publishers (Elsevier, Springer, Wiley)\n• Author compensation: $0 payment to researchers for published papers, including Nobel Prize-winning discoveries\n• Peer review labor: 15+ hours of unpaid expert review per paper, valued at $1,500-3,000 in professional consulting rates\n• Institutional subscription costs: Universities pay $10,000-50,000 annually per journal\n\n## Labor vs. Benefit Imbalance\n• Research production: Scientists conduct studies using public grants (85% of research funding from government sources)\n• Writing and submission: Researchers format, write, and submit papers without compensation\n• Quality control provision: Academic peers provide free peer review, editing, and quality assurance\n• Value capture: Publishers own copyright and charge institutions for access to their own faculty's work\n\n## Economic Extraction Quantification\n• Global market size: $28 billion annual academic publishing revenue\n• Subscription inflation: Journal prices increased 300% above inflation rate (1986-2015)\n• Profit concentration: Five publishers control 70% of scientific literature despite minimal content creation\n• Access restrictions: 75% of scientific papers locked behind paywalls\n\n## Systematic Power Asymmetries\n• Career dependency: Researchers must publish in prestigious journals for career advancement\n• Monopolistic control: Publishers control access to essential academic infrastructure\n• Copyright transfer: Authors surrender intellectual property rights for zero compensation\n• Institutional capture: Universities pay twice (funding research + subscription fees)\n\n## Global Knowledge Access Inequality\n• Developing country exclusion: 60% of research institutions in developing countries lack access to major journals\n• Public access barriers: Taxpayer-funded research inaccessible to taxpaying public\n• Innovation suppression: Restricted access slows scientific progress and collaborative research\n\n## Social Cost\nThe academic publishing system extracts $28 billion annually from public research budgets while contributing minimal value-added services."
