    "example": "Generic Drug Manufacturing for Essential Medications",
    "body": "Generic pharmaceutical production exemplifies low-profit solutions, where manufacturing life-saving medications yields minimal financial returns despite providing enormous public health value.\n\n## Profit Margin Analysis\n• Generic drug margins: 2-8% gross profit vs. 60-80% for branded pharmaceuticals\n• Manufacturing costs: Raw materials and regulatory compliance consume 85-90% of revenue\n• Price competition: Generic manufacturers compete primarily on price, driving margins to near-zero\n• Commodity pricing: Essential medications like insulin, antibiotics traded as commodities with razor-thin profits\n\n## Market Dynamics\n• FDA approval costs: $1-3 million per generic drug application with 18-month approval timeline\n• Manufacturing investment: $50-200 million facility investment for minimal return on investment\n• Price erosion: Generic drug prices decline 10-15% annually as additional manufacturers enter market\n• Volume requirements: Profitability requires massive scale (millions of units annually)\n\n## Supply Chain Vulnerability\n• Market exits: 45% of generic manufacturers exit unprofitable drug markets within 3 years\n• Production concentration: Single-source manufacturing for 40% of essential generic drugs\n• Quality compromises: Cost pressure incentivizes manufacturers to reduce quality control investments\n• Shortage frequency: 300+ drug shortages annually in US, primarily affecting low-profit generics\n\n## Investment Disincentive\n• Capital allocation: Pharmaceutical companies invest 90% of R&D budgets in high-margin branded drugs\n• Private equity avoidance: Generic manufacturing generates insufficient returns for institutional investors\n• Innovation stagnation: No financial incentive to improve manufacturing processes or develop delivery methods\n• Geographic concentration: Production concentrated in low-cost countries (India, China) creating supply vulnerabilities\n\n## Public Health Impact\n• Access limitations: Low profitability reduces manufacturer interest in producing essential medications\n• Quality variability: Cost pressures result in 15-20% higher defect rates compared to branded equivalents\n• Supply disruptions: Profit-driven market exits create critical shortages of life-saving medications\n\n## Social Value vs. Financial Return\nGeneric medications save healthcare systems $313 billion annually in the US alone while manufacturers earn <3% profit margins."
