    "example": "Industrial Agriculture and Traditional Seed Variety Extinction",
    "body": "Modern industrial agriculture exemplifies systematic jeopardization, where high-yield monoculture farming solutions designed to increase food security simultaneously threaten the genetic diversity that underpins long-term agricultural resilience.\n\n## Genetic Erosion Quantification\n• Variety loss rate: 90% of agricultural crop varieties disappeared during the 20th century\n• Wheat diversity collapse: From 2,800 varieties grown in 1903 to fewer than 50 varieties comprising 95% of global production\n• Corn genetic bottleneck: Six inbred lines account for 71% of US corn production, down from thousands of traditional varieties\n• Rice vulnerability: 10 varieties provide 95% of global rice supply, replacing 100,000+ traditional cultivars\n\n## Industrial Solution Implementation\n• High-yielding variety (HYV) promotion: Green Revolution prioritized uniform, input-responsive crop varieties\n• Seed company consolidation: Four corporations control 60% of global seed sales, promoting genetic uniformity\n• Mechanization requirements: Farm equipment designed for uniform plant heights and maturation timing\n• Chemical input optimization: Fertilizers and pesticides calibrated for specific genetic varieties\n\n## Jeopardization Mechanisms\n• Displacement effect: High-yielding varieties economically pressure farmers to abandon traditional seeds\n• Knowledge extinction: Traditional seed selection and breeding expertise lost within single generation\n• Seed banking inadequacy: Ex-situ conservation captures <5% of original genetic diversity\n• Corporate patent control: Legal restrictions prevent farmers from saving and exchanging traditional varieties\n\n## Historical Precedent Evidence\n• Irish Potato Famine (1845-1852): Genetic uniformity (single potato variety) enabled pathogen to destroy entire crop\n• Southern Corn Leaf Blight (1970): Genetic uniformity caused 15% of US corn crop loss in single season\n• Banana Panama Disease: Cavendish variety (95% of global production) threatened by fungal pathogen with no genetic resistance\n\n## Irreversibility Factor\nUnlike technological obsolescence, genetic extinction is permanent. Traditional varieties developed over millennia cannot be recreated, making this jeopardization irreversible."
