    "body": "Athletic footwear design exemplifies one-size-fits-all thinking, where women's shoes are systematically designed as scaled-down versions of men's footwear rather than accounting for fundamental anatomical differences in female foot structure and biomechanics.\n\n## Standardized Design Implementation\n• Proportional scaling methodology: Women's shoes created by reducing men's size 9 by 1.5 sizes and narrowing width uniformly\n• Last shape universality: Shoe molds designed from male foot anatomy applied to women's footwear with dimensional adjustments only\n• Heel-toe ratio standardization: Male foot proportions applied to women despite anatomical differences\n• Arch support positioning: Support structures located based on male foot anatomy without adjustment for female arch placement\n\n## Anatomical Differences Ignored\n• Heel width variance: Women's heels average 8-12mm narrower relative to forefoot width compared to men\n• Arch height differences: Women have 15-20% higher arch height requiring different support positioning\n• Toe length ratios: Women typically have proportionally longer second toes (Morton's toe)\n• Navicular bone placement: Located 15-20mm more forward in women, requiring different arch support positioning\n\n## Performance and Health Impact\n• Injury rate correlation: Women experience 2-8x higher rates of stress fractures, plantar fasciitis using \"scaled\" athletic footwear\n• Fit dissatisfaction: 88% of women report foot pain or discomfort with athletic shoes, compared to 45% of men\n• Biomechanical inefficiency: Improper heel fit causes 15-25% energy loss during athletic activities\n• Long-term consequences: 73% of women develop foot deformities from chronically ill-fitting footwear\n\n## Design Template Inadequacy\n• Heel slippage: 67% of women experience heel lift in \"women's\" athletic shoes due to incorrect heel cup design\n• Forefoot pressure: Toe box dimensions based on male proportions create excessive pressure on women's wider forefoot\n• Arch support misalignment: Support positioned for male anatomy creates mid-foot pain in 54% of female athletes\n• Gait pattern disruption: Incorrect shoe geometry forces compensatory movement patterns increasing injury risk\n\n## Recent Industry Recognition\nCompanies beginning gender-specific design (Nike, Brooks, Asics) report 25-40% higher customer satisfaction and 60% lower return rates for women's products."
